I was living in Chicago when they shot High Fidelity. I didn't know what the movie was, but I remember Lounge Ax being closed for filming for a week or so. Jeff Tweedy from Wilco was playing there like three nights a week at the time so I used to go watch him whenever I could

Music didn’t play any real part of my life growing up - I lived in a small Indiana town and my folks were not musically inclined.  My older brothers played some music but they were a good 5-9 years older so they didn’t have a lot of influence on my tastes.

My dad listened to old-school country as a kid, which I still like, and I started working at a sawmill summers when I was 14 and they played old classic rock all day in the warehouse, so I really got into Zeppelin, Hendrix, etc. which let me be all hipstery when everyone in school was into Poison
Ignoring the music aspect, country went to shit lyrically when the songs stopped being about self-loathing.
Once upon a time the songs were aware that sitting on that same barstool every night driving a busted-up truck as fundamentally sad. Now they're writting from a POV that it's a badge of pride.
I spent my summers working in a door factory or at Hoosier tire where you couldn’t hear music at either.
All I remember of the door factory was the guy who’d been working there 30 years driving a forklift which had turned his brains to mush.
An important experience to remind you to stay in school kids.
lol, yep

We had a guy named Al. He'd go to the gas station at first break and buy a gallon of chocolate milk, and leave it next to his station to drink from all day. This is an open-air sawmill, so it would get into the 90's. The last quarter of the gallon would be like syrup. He'd still drink it though.
My brother in law used to leave 2-liters of genetic soda in his car all day and then drink it at night when he’d get off work.
